## 1. 📈 NIM — Net Interest Margin

People deposit money in a bank → bank gives loans at interest → also pays depositors some interest. **NIM is the difference between these two.**

> In simpler words — how much the bank earns on loan interest vs. how much it pays to depositors.

**Formula:**
```
NIM = (Interest Income - Interest Expense) / Average Earning Assets × 100
```

**🧾 Real Example — HDFC Bank:**

| | Amount |
|---|---|
| Interest Income (loans se) | ₹1,000 Crore |
| Interest Expense (depositors ko) | ₹600 Crore |
| Average Earning Assets | ₹10,000 Crore |
```
NIM = (1000 - 600) / 10,000 × 100 = 4%
```

**📊 Industry Benchmark:**
- 🇮🇳 Indian banks NIM typically **3–4%**
- ⚠️ Falling NIM = bank profitability at risk

---

## 2. 😨 NPA Ratio — Non Performing Assets

One of the **scariest and most critical metrics.** How much loan amount is not returned.

**Formula:**
```
NPA Ratio = (Gross NPA / Gross Advances) × 100
```

**📊 Industry Benchmark:**

| Status | NPA % |
|---|---|
| ✅ Healthy | < 2% |
| 🚨 Danger Zone | > 5% (RBI sends notice) |

**Gross NPA vs Net NPA:**

| | Definition |
|---|---|
| 📌 Gross NPA | Total bad loans |
| 📌 Net NPA | Gross NPA - Provisions |

---

## 3. 💹 ROA — Return on Assets

Are the bank's assets being **effectively used for profit making?**

**Formula:**
```
ROA = Net Profit / Average Total Assets × 100
```

**📊 Benchmark:**

| ROA | Status |
|---|---|
| > 1.5% | 🏆 Excellent |
| > 1% | ✅ Good |
| < 0.5% | ⚠️ Struggling |

---

## 4. 👥 ROE — Return on Equity

How much return shareholders get on their investment. **Important metric for investors.**

**Formula:**
```
ROE = Net Profit / Shareholders Equity × 100
```

> 📊 **Benchmark:** 15%+ ROE is excellent in banking 🏆

**ROA vs ROE — Quick Comparison:**

| | ROA | ROE |
|---|---|---|
| 📌 Measures | Asset efficiency | Shareholder returns |
| 👤 Important for | Management | Investors |
| 🧮 Formula | Profit / Assets | Profit / Equity |
| ✅ Good Value | > 1% | > 15% |

---

## 5. ⚙️ Cost-to-Income Ratio (CIR)

Measures the bank's **operating efficiency.**

**Formula:**
```
CIR = Operating Expenses / Operating Income × 100
```

**📊 Benchmark:**

| CIR | Status |
|---|---|
| < 40% | 🏆 Efficient |
| 40–50% | ✅ Average |
| > 60% | ⚠️ Overspending |

> 💡 That's why banks are closing branches and pushing digital — to improve their CIR!

---

## 6. 🛡️ Capital Adequacy Ratio (CAR)

If many loans default — **can the bank survive?** CAR is the cushion to absorb risk.

**Formula:**
```
CAR = (Tier 1 Capital + Tier 2 Capital) / Risk Weighted Assets × 100
```

| Capital Type | Definition |
|---|---|
| 🏦 Tier 1 | Core capital — equity, retained earnings |
| 📄 Tier 2 | Supplementary — bonds, etc. |

**📊 Minimum Requirements:**
- 🇮🇳 RBI minimum = **9%**
- 🌍 Basel III global standard = **8%**

---

## 7. ⚖️ Loan-to-Deposit Ratio (LDR)

What % of deposits collected was given out as loans?

**Formula:**
```
LDR = Total Loans / Total Deposits × 100
```

**📊 Benchmark:**

| LDR | Status |
|---|---|
| 80–90% | 🎯 Sweet Spot |
| < 60% | 📉 Underutilizing deposits |
| > 95% | 🚨 Low liquidity, risky! |

---

## 8. 💼 AUM — Assets Under Management

Primarily for **wealth management and investment firms.** How much money clients have given to manage.

**Formula:**
```
AUM = Total Market Value of All Managed Investments
```

---

## 9. 📱 Digital Adoption Rate

How many customers use app/internet banking vs. branch visits. **The metric of the future** — digital customers cost much less to serve. 🚀

**Formula:**
```
Digital Adoption Rate = (Digital Active Users / Total Active Customers) × 100
```

---

## 10. 🚨 Fraud Rate

How many transactions are fraudulent. **A major risk metric for banks.**

**Formula:**
```
Fraud Rate = (Fraudulent Transactions / Total Transactions) × 100
```
```
Fraud Loss Rate = Fraud Loss Amount / Total Transaction Amount × 100
```

